href - Hyper reference attribute
When you press the exclamation mark at the beginning of an HTML file and enter, the boiler template is inserted. Example below;

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Document</title>
</head>
<body>
    
</body>
</html>


WHAT IS AN ATTRIBUTE?

In HTML, an attribute provides additional information about an HTML element. Attributes are always specified within the opening tag of an HTML element and typically come in name/value pairs.

Here's a breakdown of what attributes mean in HTML: 

Enhance Elements: Attributes modify the default behavior or appearance of an HTML element. For example, the src attribute in an <img> tag specifies the image file to display, and the href attribute in an <a> tag specifies the URL for the link.

Provide Information: They offer more details about an element. The alt attribute for an <img> tag provides alternative text for screen readers or when the image cannot be displayed.

Name/Value Pairs: Attributes are typically written as name="value". The name identifies the characteristic being defined (e.g., class, id, style), and the value provides the specific setting for that characteristic (e.g., "my-class", "unique-id", "color: blue;").

Placement: Attributes are placed within the opening tag of an HTML element, separated from the tag name and other attributes by spaces.

Examples:
href attribute: Specifies the URL for a hyperlink.







CSS - Cascading Style Sheet
We have 2 types; Inline CSS, External CSS and Internal CSS



Inline is within the lines of various elememts in HTML code e.g.
<h1 style="color: purple; background-color: beige;">The Real John</h1>



Internal CSS ia also within the HTML code but in the head section or inside the head tag of the code e.g.

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">


<head>

    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>The Real John</title>



    <style>

        /*1. Tag Name*/
        h1{
            color: rebeccapurple;
            background-color: rgb(101, 255, 255);
            height: 15;
            width: 15;
        }

        /*2. Class Name*/
        .name{
            color: yellow;
            background-color: tomato;
        }

            /*3. ID Name*/
        #heading{
            color: black;
            background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);
        }
        
    </style>



</head>



We have what we call Selector Specificity; The higher the Selector Specificity